eanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lacon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Lacon in Wem (Shrops). This name has probably been confused with or absorbed by   Lakin   (1), especially in counties adjoining Shrops, such as Staffs.","2  English: while the name in Yorks could be that in (1) through migration, its appearance in late 14th-century Clint in the north-west of WR Yorks, and the persistent final  <i>-can</i> in most early forms of the surname, suggest that it may have had a different but unknown origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Laken","meanings":["1  English:  see  Lakin  .","2  English:  see  Lacon  ."]},{"name":"Laking","meanings":["English:  see  Lacon   and   Lakin  ."]},{"name":"Lakin","meanings":["Americanized form of Jewish <i>Leykin</i> (from Belarus), a metronymic from <i>Leyke</i>, a pet form of the Yiddish female personal name <i>Leye</i>, from the Hebrew female personal name <i>Lea</i>, from which English <i>Leah</i> is derived (see Genesis 29: 16) + the Slavic possessive suffix <i>-in</i>.","English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Lawkin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Law-</i> (a pet form of the personal name <i>Laurence</i>; see   Lawrence  ). Compare   Law   1 and   Larkin  ."]}]},{"name":"Gunale,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a variant of   Gundel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gundel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans.","South German (also <b>Gündel</b>): from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names beginning with <i>gund</i> ‘battle’."]}]},{"name":"Constantino","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Constantinus</i>, a derivative of <i>Constans</i>;  see  Constant .  In early modern English the names <i>Constant</i> and <i>Constantine</i> were not always clearly distinguished. The Roman emperor  Constantine the Great  (  ?288–337 ) is specially honoured in the Christian Church as the first Christian emperor. The name was also borne by three kings of medieval Scotland, where it represents an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name   Conn  , and is a traditional name in the Phipps (Marquesses of Normanby) family."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Constantino I de Lacon Gunale, Judge of Arborea was born about 1065, in Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy as the son of Gonario II de Serra, Judge of Arborea and Elena de Orru di Gunale. He had at least 2 sons with Ana De Zorri. He died about 1131, in Arborea, Sardinia, Italy, at the age of 68, and was buried in Sassari, Sardinia, Italy."},"et":{"about 1065–about 1131":"umbes 1065–umbes 1131","1065–1131":"1065–1131","–1175":"–1175","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1055–1103":"1055–1103","1080–1144":"1080–1144","–1147":"–1147","1050–1163":"1050–1163","1080":"1080","from about 1101 to 1131":"umbes 1101 kuni 1131","1055":"1055","1175":"1175","1131":"1131","1065":"1065","1163":"1163","1050":"1050","1103":"1103","1147":"1147","1144":"1144","about 1065":"umbes 1065","about 1131":"umbes 1131","Arborea, Sardinia, Italy":"Arborea, Sardegna, Itaalia","Arborea, Oristano, Sardinia, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Itaalia","Basilica della Santissima Trinità di Saccargia-Codrongianos, 6364, Sassari, Sardegna, Italie":"Sassari, Sardegna, Itaalia","Arborea, Oristan, Sardegna, Italy":"Arborea, Oristano, Sardegna, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1065–about 1131